Wash and dry all produce. Bring a large #pot{} of @salt{}ed water to a boil. Quarter @zucchini{1} lengthwise, then cut crosswise into ¼-inch-thick triangles. Halve and peel @shallot{1}, then thinly slice. Halve @heirloom grape tomatoes{4%ounce} lengthwise. Pick a few @parsley{1/4%ounce} leaves from stems for garnish, then finely chop the rest of the bunch.

Heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{1%tablespoon} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add zucchini and cook, tossing, until browned, ~{5-7%minutes}. Add shallot, a pinch of @chili flakes{1%teaspoon} (to taste), and a drizzle of olive oil. Cook, tossing, until shallot is softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Once water is boiling, add @mushroom ravioli{9%ounce} to pot. Reduce heat to low. Cook until tender and floating to the top, about ~{4%minutes}. Carefully scoop out and reserve ½ cup pasta cooking water, then drain.

Once shallot is softened, stir tomatoes into pan, then reduce heat to low. Stir in @sour cream{4%tablespoon}, @veggie stock concentrate{1}, half the @Parmesan cheese{1/4%cup}, and ¼ cup pasta cooking water. Season with @salt{}, @pepper{}, chopped parsley, and more chili flakes to taste.

Add ravioli to pan, increase heat to medium, and gently toss to coat ravioli in sauce. Cook until sauce thickens slightly, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> TIP: Add more pasta cooking water, if needed, to give sauce a loose consistency.

Divide ravioli mixture between plates, then garnish with remaining Parmesan and reserved parsley leaves and serve.